          "title": "The two eagles and the vine — a political tragedy in botanical form",
          "body": "The parable's three characters — the first great eagle, the planted vine, and the second great eagle — map precisely onto Nebuchadnezzar, Zedekiah, and Pharaoh. The imagery is designed to expose the absurdity of Zedekiah's diplomacy: a vine already planted in good soil beside abundant waters (17:5, 8), given everything it needs to survive as a vassal, voluntarily bends its roots toward a second eagle (17:7) who offers nothing the first eagle has not already provided. The vine's action is not strategic; it is suicidal. The east wind — the scorching sirocco, God's instrument of desert judgment throughout the Hebrew Bible (Hosea 13:15; Jonah 4:8) — will do what no political reversal can undo: the vine will completely wither (17:10). The rhetorical questions of verses 9-10 are not genuine queries but verdicts dressed as questions. Daniel Block (NICOT, Ezekiel 1-24, 1997) observes that the vine imagery deliberately recalls the classic prophetic image of Israel as God's vineyard (Isaiah 5; Psalm 80) — the vine that bends toward Egypt is betraying not only Babylon but the God who planted Israel in the land in the first place."
