          "body": "Verse 20 contains one of the chapter's most striking images: 'I will spread My net over him, and he will be caught in My snare. Then I will bring him to Babylon and enter into judgment with him there.' The net and snare are hunting images — God as the sovereign who outmaneuvers every escape route. But the second half is more surprising: God brings Zedekiah to Babylon not merely for execution but for judicial proceeding (shaphat — to enter into judgment). Babylon is not only the place of exile; it becomes the courtroom of divine justice. God does not outsource the verdict to Nebuchadnezzar — He conducts His own proceedings there. This is consistent with Ezekiel's broader theology: Babylon is God's instrument (21:18-23), but God is always the principal agent. The God who spread His net in Babylon is the same God who will spread His cedar over the nations in verses 22-24. Both net and cedar are expressions of His absolute sovereignty over the stage where empires perform."
