          "body": "The transition from verse 21 to verse 22 is one of the most abrupt and glorious pivots in Ezekiel. No condition is given, no bridge is constructed, no human agency is invoked. God simply announces: 'I will also take a sprig from the lofty top of the cedar and set it out.' The chapter that began with Nebuchadnezzar plucking the cedar's top now ends with God plucking the cedar's top — and the difference is everything. What the empire did for exploitation and subjugation, God does for restoration and exaltation. The sprig is described as 'tender' (rakh, 17:22) — the same word used in Proverbs 4:3 for a child, and in Isaiah 53:2 for the Servant who 'grew up before Him like a tender shoot.' The vulnerability is the point: what God plants in apparent weakness will become a 'stately cedar' (17:23) under which birds of every kind nest. The echo of Daniel 4:12 — the great tree whose branches shelter all birds and animals — is unmistakable and intentional. Jesus draws the same image into His parable of the mustard seed (Matthew 13:31-32; Mark 4:30-32), where a tiny seed becomes a tree sheltering birds of every kind. The parabolic form, the tree imagery, the universal gathering — all three features connect Ezekiel 17:22-24 to the kingdom of God as Jesus announces it."
