          "body": "Ezekiel's signature closing formula appears twice in this chapter and in two different registers. In verse 21, after the judgment: 'you will know that I, the Lord, have spoken.' In verse 24, after the restoration: 'all the trees of the field will know that I am the Lord.' The first knowledge is narrow — the exilic community, humbled by the fall of Jerusalem, will finally acknowledge that Ezekiel's word was God's word. The second knowledge is cosmic — 'all the trees of the field,' a metonym for the nations, will recognize God's sovereign reversals. The formula yada (to know) in Ezekiel is never merely cognitive — it is the recognition that follows encounter with the living God acting in history. It is forced acknowledgment, not intellectual assent. Moshe Greenberg (Ezekiel 1-20, AB, 1983) identifies this 'recognition formula' as Ezekiel's central theological concern: God acts in history so that His identity as Yahweh is undeniably established. Every judgment and every restoration in the book is calibrated toward this end. The chapter that began with a riddle ('Do you not know?' 17:12) ends with universal knowing (17:24) — and the knowing is God's gift, wrested from the ruins of every human pretension to sovereignty."
